      "text": "How Much Do YouTube Shorts Pay?"
    },
    {
      "id": "t8",
      "tag": "p",
      "text": "YouTube Shorts pays significantly less per view than long-form content — roughly"
    },
    {
      "id": "t9",
      "tag": "strong",
      "text": "$0.03 to $0.07 per 1,000 views"
    },
    {
      "id": "t10",
      "tag": "p",
      "text": "compared to $3–$6 RPM for standard videos. That's 50–100× less per view. Yet Shorts remains strategically valuable because its viral potential brings audiences to your channel that never would have found you otherwise."
    },
    {
      "id": "t11",
      "tag": "strong",
      "text": "The Shorts strategy:"
    },
    {
      "id": "t12",
      "tag": "p",
      "text": "Use Shorts as a growth engine to grow your subscriber base, then convert those subscribers into long-form viewers who generate 50–100× more ad revenue per view."
    },
    {
      "id": "t13",
      "tag": "h2",
      "text": "YouTube Shorts Monetization Explained"
    },
    {
      "id": "t14",
      "tag": "p",
      "text": "Shorts uses a"
    },
    {
      "id": "t15",
      "tag": "strong",
      "text": "pooled ad revenue model"
    },
    {
      "id": "t16",
      "tag": "p",
      "text": "distinct from standard YouTube monetization:"
    },
    {
      "id": "t17",
      "tag": "span",
      "text": "Ads are shown between videos in the Shorts Feed — not on individual Shorts themselves."
    },
    {
      "id": "t18",
      "tag": "span",
      "text": "Revenue from those ads enters a shared monthly pool."
    },
    {
      "id": "t19",
      "tag": "span",
      "text": "Creators receive 45% of revenue proportional to their share of total Shorts views."
    },
    {
      "id": "t20",
      "tag": "span",
      "text": "Effective RPM is far lower than long-form due to the shared, indirect structure."
    },
